Globalization diseases
Globalization is being put to the test like never before.
Its tensions simmer everywhere.
The vast majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia are stagnating or struggling in an economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk a new recession.
War now threatens in Iraq.
For advocates of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its benefits apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they are barely sufficient.
Some regions of the world have gained significant advantages from globalization, particularly East Asia and China in recent years.
Some regions have nonetheless gained meager advantages from it, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The U.S. government claims that poor countries are responsible for most of the problems they face.
The slow growth in Africa, American leaders assert, is caused by the ineffectiveness of African governments.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has seen a decline in living standards over the past two decades while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of government quality (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
Countries with large populations and therefore large domestic markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with small populations.
(As with all such economic trends, there are counterexamples.)
Coastal countries tend to perform better than landlocked countries.
Countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries bordering rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to perform better than those located far from the main markets.
These differences are of great significance.
If wealthy countries do not address these structural problems, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shift the blame onto unlucky countries by claiming they are culturally or politically unsuited to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper poverty pockets but also intensify unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to adopt a more serious approach to globalization than what wealthy countries, and particularly the United States, offer.
This approach must start with the most urgent task, namely addressing the fundamental needs of the world's poorest peoples.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated primarily through better governance within their own countries.
But in others, a honest look at the gathered evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty involve diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distances from markets, etc.
A honest assessment would further indicate that the poorest countries lack the ability to gather sufficient funds to resolve such problems on their own.
Rather than seeing rich countries give more lectures on the bad governance of poor countries, real solutions require that rich countries provide sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most entrenched barriers.
A case will illustrate this situation starkly.
The control of diseases requires a healthcare system capable of providing survival medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
This system costs at least about 40 dollars per person and per year.
This sum represents only a grain of sand for rich countries who spend systematically more than 2,000 dollars per person and per year on health, but it exceeds the means of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual revenues of 200 dollars per person.
A functioning healthcare system would cost more than the entire revenue of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires us to think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Rather than scolding the poor for their "sins," we must offer prudent diagnoses, as any good doctor would, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that hinder their growth and economic development.
In regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem primarily stems from geographical isolation.
There, the task consists of building roads, air links, and internet connectivity to help these remote regions establish productive links with the world.
Rich countries must contribute to financing these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges relate to disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
A greater foreign aid is once again required.
In other regions, the main problems relate to a lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the inherent complexities of globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all Washington consensus is outdated.
Before the war, it is urgent to tackle the hard task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this if we remove the ideological blinders of the rich and mobilize a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
